# .semgrepignore — VSP Security Platform
#
# Path globs that Semgrep CI (security-deep.yml `Semgrep wide packs`)
# should skip. Two reasons something belongs here:
#
#   (a) The path is test fixtures / example data / sample exploits —
#       the WHOLE POINT is to have intentionally vulnerable patterns
#       for our scanners or test suite to detect.
#   (b) The path is dev-only / never deployed to prod, so wide-pack
#       hits there are noise.
#
# For real production code, prefer inline `// nosemgrep:rule-id`
# comments with rationale over globbing the file out here.

# ── Test fixtures, integration tests, dev stubs ────────────────────
**/*_test.go
**/testdata/**
internal/integration/**
internal/store/storetest/**
internal/testutil/**
cmd/dev-stub/**

# ── Semgrep rule files (intentionally contain bad-pattern examples) ──
scripts/lib/semgrep-rules.yml
**/.semgrep/**

# ── Migration SQL (CREATE/DROP statements look like injection to taint
#    analysers but are pure schema DDL — Semgrep should never scan these)
internal/migrate/sql/**
**/*.sql

# ── Patches dir contains intentionally incomplete code snippets for
#    bug-reproduction (no main(), unused functions, etc.) ──────────
patches/**

# ── Build / vendor / generated ─────────────────────────────────────
**/vendor/**
**/node_modules/**
**/*.pb.go
**/*_generated.go

# ── nginx config patches — request_host_used is intentional behind
#    a trusted load balancer (X-Forwarded-Host already validated) ──
patches/perf/04-disable-nginx-ratelimit/**

# ── Documentation / changelog / sample CLI args ────────────────────
docs/**
CHANGELOG*.md
**/*.md

# ── Marketing / report HTML (not application code) ─────────────────
docs/governance/**

# ── Third-party JS we ship as-is (CDN-mirrored libraries) ──────────
static/js/vendor/**
static/lib/**
